{"id":649,"date":"2012-12-27T09:19:42","date_gmt":"2012-12-27T06:19:42","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/qidwaiwelfare.com\/?p=649"},"modified":"2012-12-27T09:46:08","modified_gmt":"2012-12-27T06:46:08","slug":"solar-water-heaters-installed-at-orphan-homes","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/qidwaiwelfare.com\/solar-water-heaters-installed-at-orphan-homes\/","title":{"rendered":"Solar Water Heaters Installed at Orphan Homes"},"content":{"rendered":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Winters can be extremely cold in Islamabad with\u00a0temperatures\u00a0dropping to single digits between sunset and dusk. Performing ablutions for prayers and taking showers can be difficult and can also be of health hazard for small children,\u00a0especially\u00a0without hot water. So this winter we installed two 315 liters (70 gallons) solar powered water heaters at our orphan homes in Naval Anchorage, Islamabad. The solar water heaters are programmed to provide 630 liters (140 gallons) of hot water of approximately 90 degree\u00a0Celsius temperature three times a day (total of 1890 liters).\u00a0This works out to approximately 26.25 liter (5.8 gallons) per person per day.<\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We know that this is not sufficient hot water as the average hot water consumption is\u00a0approximately\u00a050 litters (11 gallons) per person per day. But this is a pilot project and we plan to expand and add additional water heaters in the future.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Winters can be extremely cold in Islamabad with\u00a0temperatures\u00a0dropping to single digits between sunset and dusk. Performing ablutions for prayers and [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_was_ever_published":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_access":"","_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id":